Metadata: Marine natural products from the seychelles

"Proceedings of Troisieme symposium sur les substances naturelles d'interet biologique de la region Pacifique-â€‹Asie," C. Debitus, P. Armade, D. Laurant, and J.-P. Cosson, eds., pp 257- 264, August 20-26, 1991.

Seychelles, a group of islands in the Indian Ocean, yielded 93 sponges, 14 soft corals, 10 tunicates, 4 zoanthids, 3 hard corals, 2 algae, and an anemone in a collecting expedition. The crude methanolic extracts of 124 samples were screened against the Gram-positive bacteria "Staphylococcus aureus" and "Bacillus subtilis", the Gram negative bacteria "Escherichia coli" and "Pseudomonas aeruginosa", and the fungus "Candida albicans". Seven extracts were very active against all microbes; however, all of these extracts were from organisms familiar from prior studies. The bioactivity data were unexceptional but the 1H NMR spectra revealed several unusual compounds.
